Across the last few years we keep hearing the same kind of conversation in three different rooms. Software developers ask what they could change in their own code to lower its environmental footprint, but most of the answers they hit are either too abstract ("write efficient code") or too far down a research rabbit-hole to apply on a Monday. Computer science teachers say they'd like to fold a sustainability strand into their programming courses but cannot find a resource they'd feel comfortable assigning to a class without first vetting every page themselves. And in tech-company strategy meetings, someone raises "we should probably be doing something about our software's carbon footprint" and the room agrees in principle, then the topic dies because nobody knows what that something concretely is.

We'd like to commission a website that does something useful with this gap. The shape we have in mind is loose on purpose. It could lean editorial — a place that profiles practitioners and projects doing notable work on sustainable programming, the kind of site a developer comes back to for inspiration. It could lean practical — a toolkit of frameworks, checklists, and measurement pointers a developer pulls up while writing code. It could lean educational — content structured the way a teacher would want to assign it, with reading order and exercises. Or it could centre on case studies — a small set of in-depth stories about teams that adopted green coding practices, the kind of thing a startup founder reads before pitching their own board. We don't yet know which of those it should mostly be, and we suspect "all four at once" would dilute every one of them.

The primary readers we have in mind are working software developers — the people whose day-to-day choices the site is meant to inform. But we'd want the site to also be useful for a computer science student starting out who is curious about this whole area, and for a CS teacher integrating sustainability into a programming course they already run. There is also a quieter audience we'd like to keep in view: developers who personally are already convinced and now want to bring sustainable practices into their team. Their need isn't the case for sustainability — they have that. Their need is something specific they can hand to a skeptical colleague or manager in a meeting tomorrow. Their experience of the site is not the same as a newcomer's, and we'd rather not flatten them into a single audience.

What we hope comes out of it: a developer who lands on the site treats it as a place they'd return to, not a one-time read. A teacher who finds it feels they could assign a page without doing a separate quality check first. An already-convinced advocate has a specific link they can drop into a workplace conversation to move the conversation forward. More diffusely, fewer of those tech-meeting conversations that end with "we should do something" and no follow-through.

A few things the site should not try to be. It is not the venue for publishing original academic research on green software — those venues exist already and the website should not pretend to be one. It is not a certification authority or a credentialing body issuing badges for sustainable code. And it is not itself a measurement or linting tool — at most it might point at the ones that already exist.
